notesStmt.note: Title supplied by cataloger (Zacour-Hirsch); title page presents as the author the name Blasius, with the word Bellunensis (meaning from the northern Italian town of Belluno) added in Egyptian letters; date 1682 is in Hebrew.
Alphabetum Hebraicum is based on Aldo Manuzio.

Music: Contains examples of note values and scales in various keys on 5-line staves in black ink (f. 95v-97v) and of psalm intonations and the Magnificat in 8 tones in black square notation on 14-line staves in red ink (f. 101r-106r).

msContents.textLang: Italian and Latin, with examples in Hebrew and Greek

msItem.title: Regola per imperare il canto figurato [e] gregoriano, f. 95v [=86v]
Modo ... per trovare ... la prima domenica dell?advento, f. 117r [=108r]

supportDesc.extent: 112 leaves : 160 x 97 mm. bound to 171 x 105 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, 112; [iv], 1-20, 22-86, 95-98, [i], 99-110, 112-[117]; contemporary foliation in ink, upper right recto. Folio 21 appears to have been cut out; blank folio preceding f. 99; f. 107-116 blank, f. 87-94 cut out).

decoDesc.decoNote: Alphabetical tables; astronomical diagrams in red, blue, and green ink (f. 68v-84v); "Tabula Paschalis antiqua Reformata" with a movable calendar tipped in (f. 85v-86v); a drawing of a Guidonian hand (f. 98v), illustrated title page (f. [iii] recto) depicts the ouroboros, the Nativity, the resurrected Christ, and a hand holding a quill pen, with "Blasius" and undeciphered title.
Illustration, Stack of books, Inside front cover
Drawing, Resurrected Christ, f. iii recto
Drawing, Hand holding quill, f. iii recto

binding.p: Contemporary blind-stamped pigskin with 3 watercolor illustrations depicting a stack of books with the word Leges; spiders with the words Sicut aranearum; and a spider's web with the word Tela (inside upper cover).
